🎯 2. Interview Tricks (This is GOLD)
🔹 Trick 1: Always explain in 3 steps

When asked:

👉 “Explain this regex: ^\\d+”

Say:

^ → start of string

\\d → digit

+ → one or more
👉 So it extracts digits from the beginning

🔹 Trick 2: Use real-life examples

Instead of theory, say:

“We use regex to extract phone numbers, IDs, or names from messy text.”

🔹 Trick 3: Mention limitation

Say this to sound advanced:

“str_extract() returns only the first match. For multiple matches, we use str_extract_all().”

🔹 Trick 4: Show R-specific knowledge

👉 VERY IMPORTANT:

“In R, we use \\d instead of \d because backslash is an escape character.”

🔹 Trick 5: Compare patterns (Interviewers LOVE this)

| Pattern | Meaning         |
| ------- | --------------- |
| `\\d+`  | digits anywhere |
| `^\\d+` | digits at start |
| `\\d+$` | digits at end   |


🔹 Trick 6: Say this line (impressive)

“Regex is powerful for data cleaning and preprocessing, especially in text data.”

📄 3. Cheat Sheet (Save This 🔥)

🔹 BASIC PATTERNS
| Pattern    | Meaning               |
| ---------- | --------------------- |
| `\\d`      | digit (0–9)           |
| `[A-Za-z]` | letters               |
| `.`        | any character         |
| `\\s`      | space                 |
| `\\w`      | word (letter + digit) |


🔹 QUANTIFIERS
| Symbol | Meaning      |
| ------ | ------------ |
| `+`    | one or more  |
| `*`    | zero or more |
| `?`    | optional     |

🔹 POSITION

| Symbol | Meaning |
| ------ | ------- |
| `^`    | start   |
| `$`    | end     |

🔹 COMMON FUNCTIONS (R)

From stringr package:
str_extract()      # first match
str_extract_all()  # all matches
str_detect()       # TRUE/FALSE
str_replace()      # replace text

QUICK EXAMPLES
str_extract("abc123", "\\d+")     # "123"
str_extract("123abc", "^\\d+")    # "123"
str_extract("abc123", "\\d+$")    # "123"
str_extract("123abc", "[A-Za-z]+")# "abc"


